#Text=George Wilkins
#Text=For other people named Main Page , see Main Page ( disambiguation ) .
#Text=George Wilkins ( died 1618 ) [ 1 ] was an English dramatist and pamphleteer best known for his probable collaboration with William Shakespeare on the play Pericles , Prince of Tyre .
#Text=By profession he was an inn-keeper , but he was also apparently involved in criminal activities .
#Text=Life
#Text=Wilkins was an inn-keeper in Cow-Cross , London , an area that was " notorious as a haunt of whores and thieves " . [ 2 ]

column1: #Text=Most biographical information about him derives from his regular appearance in criminal court records for thievery and acts of violence .
#Text=Many of the charges against him involved violence against women , including kicking a pregnant woman in the belly , and knocking down and stomping another woman .
#Text=The latter appears in other records as a known " bawd " , or keeper of prostitutes .
#Text=These facts have led to the suggestion that his inn functioned as a brothel and that Wilkins was a procurer , or pimp . [ 2 ] [ 3 ]
#Text=Wilkins was associated with the King 's Men , and their chief playwright William Shakespeare , during the latter 's last working years as a dramatist .
#Text=Shakespeare and Wilkins were both witnesses in the case of Bellott v Mountjoy in 1612 ; in his deposition he described himself as a " victualler . "
#Text=Works
#Text=He is first heard of as the author of a pamphlet on the Three Miseries of Barbary , which dates from 1606 . [ 4 ]
#Text=He then collaborated in 1607 with William Rowley and John Day in The Travels of the Three English Brothers , a dramatisation of the real-life adventures of the Sherley brothers .
#Text=In the same year Wilkins wrote The Miseries of Enforced Marriage .
#Text=This play is based on the story of Walter Calverley , whose identity is thinly disguised under the name of " Scarborough . "
#Text=This man had killed his two children and had attempted to murder his wife .

#Text=The play originally had a tragic ending , but as played in 1607 , ended in comedy and the story stopped short before the catastrophe , perhaps because of objections raised by Mrs. Calverley 's family , the Cobhams .
#Text=The crime itself is dealt with in a short play , A Yorkshire Tragedy of uncertain authorship .
#Text=Pericles

#Text=A number of studies have attributed to Wilkins a share in Shakespeare 's Pericles , Prince of Tyre ( which does not appear in Shakespeare 's First Folio , but was published only in a textually corrupt quarto ) .
#Text=This may have been collaboration , or perhaps Wilkins was the original author of Pericles and Shakespeare remodelled it , or vice versa .

#Text=However it may be , Wilkins published in 1608 a novel entitled The Painful Adventures of Pericles , Prynce of Tyre , described as " the true history of Pericles as it was lately presented by ... John Gower " ( who serves as narrator in the play ) .

column1: #Text=This follows the play very closely .

#Text=The editors of the 1986 Oxford Edition of Shakespeare make the assumption that Wilkins was the co-author of Pericles and draw heavily upon The Painful Adventures in their controversial reconstructed text of the play .
#Text=Wilkins is thought to have contributed most of the first two acts of the play , while Shakespeare wrote the last three .
